================================================================================
Duration: 110s (target ≤ 5 min — PASS on duration)
Status: PARTIAL — up + status + doctor green, down failed cleanup.

PASSES (verifies prior fixes live):
  ✓ runnerkit up succeeded, runner ID 26 registered (Path B sudo prompt fired
    once via TTY, accepted password — Plan 06-06 path works).
  ✓ /opt/actions-runner/runnerkit-*/config.sh present on remote
  ✓ /opt/actions-runner/runnerkit-*/.runner sentinel present
  ✓ runnerkit status — Health: ready
  ✓ "SSH OK reachable, host key matched" ← VERIFIES Plan 06-11 Bug 24 fix live
  ✓ "Service OK active"
  ✓ runnerkit doctor — only time_unsynchronized warning (expected, NTP not configured)

FAILURE — Bug 28 (NEW, root-caused via in-flight trace):
  runnerkit down --yes:
    • host_registration: pending remote_cleanup_pending
    • runner_files: failed sudo: a terminal is required to read the password
    • RKD-CLEAN-003 emitted

  Root cause (traced via temporary fmt.Fprintf in down.go gate, since reverted):
    [BUG25-TRACE] gate: targetErr=<nil> needsAnyRemoteSudo=true sshReachable=true
    [BUG25-TRACE] probe-direct: rc=1 err=exit status 1
    [BUG25-TRACE] probe: needs=false probeErr=<nil>

  internal/cli/down.go:436 probeSudoNeedsPassword:
        result, err := executor.Run(ctx, target, ...)
        if err != nil {
            return false, nil   ← BUG: real SSH executor returns
                                   `err = exit status 1` for any non-zero rc;
                                   probe early-returns "no password needed"
                                   regardless of stderr markers.
        }

  Plan 06-11 Bug 25 fix (gate dropped sshReachable) is correct logic-wise but
  ineffective because the probe still bails before reaching the marker check.
  The Bug 25 unit test used a fake executor that returns err=nil for non-zero
  exit, so the regression slipped past CI.

  Fix shape: probeSudoNeedsPassword should NOT early-return on err — it should
  inspect result.ExitCode and result.Stderr regardless (a non-zero exit is
  expected; err is just Go's wrapper around the exit status). One-line fix +
  a real-SSH-style executor test mode.

